We observe here that the last simulation (year 100) is at 4th position for each species.

For all species number \(i\in[1,32]\), we want to compare the year 0 biomass map to the year 100 biomass map, i.e. compare the map number \(id_{0} = 100*(i-1)+i\) to the map number \(id_{100} = id_{0}+3\).

II.B. Variables used

II.B.1. Construction of the migration variable

For each species, at each scenario, the mean shift in coordinates and the mean shift in altitude are calculated.

The mean West-Est shift \(Xshift_{ij}\) and the mean North-South shift \(Yshift_{ij}\) of the species \(i\) in the scenario \(j\) are calculated as :

\[ \begin{align*} Xshift_{ij} & = C_{ij}(t=100)_{x}-C_{ij}(t=0)_{x} \\ Yshift_{ij} & = C_{ij}(t=100)_{y}-C_{ij}(t=0)_{y} \\ \end{align*} \]

With :

  • \(C_{ij}(t=0)_{x}\) and \(C_{ij}(t=0)_{y}\) the two coordinates of the centroid of the biomass of the species \(i \in [1,32]\) in the scenario \(j \in [1,2]\) and at the initial conditions (at year 0). This centroid is calculated weighed by the biomass of each poin.

  • \(C_{ij}(t=100)_{x}\) and \(C_{ij}(t=100)_{y}\) the coordinates of the same centroid but calculated at the end of the simulation (at year 100).

The mean altitude shift \(Zshift_{ij}\) of the species \(i\) in the scenario \(j\) is calculated as :

\[Zshift_{ij} = \overline{Z_{ij}(t=100)}-\overline{Z_{ij}(t=0)}\]

With :

  • \(\overline{Z_{ij}(t=0)}\) the mean altitude of all the points containing the species \(i \in [1,32]\) in the scenario \(j \in [1,2]\) and at the initial conditions (at year 0). This mean altitude is calculated weighed by the biomass of each poin.

\(\overline{Z_{ij}(t=100)}\) the same, but at the end of the simulation (at year 100).

These three operations are done in each one of the scenarios, and all the results are compiled in the dataframe Results.

Results = c("Name", "Scenario", "Migration_x", "Migration_y","Migration_Altitude", "Migration_SoilMoist" ,"Distribution", "Group")

II.B.2. Loop

For the species \(i\), the previous calculus are done for each one of the scenarios.

for(i in (1:32)){
  name = ListNamesTot[i]
  id0 = 100*(i-1)+i
  id100 = id0+3
  
  ### Scenario 1 (BAU only):
  
  ## Centroid of the intitial distribution of biomass of the species i(t=0)
  BAU_year0NoDef = paste(BAU_input,BAU_ListData[id0],sep="") %>% raster()
  BAU_year0 = raster(vals=getValues(BAU_year0NoDef),
                    nrow=NrowRef,ncol=NcolRef,resolution=ResRef,
                    xmn=XminRef, xmx=XmaxRef,ymn =YminRef,ymx=YmaxRef,crs=CRSRef)
  BAU_points0 = rasterToPoints(BAU_year0, fun = function(x){x>=1}, spatial = T)
  BAU_Centroid0 = wt.centroid(BAU_points0,"layer", sp=T)
  
  # Mean altitude of all the points, weighted by the biomass
  BAU_alt0_df = raster::extract(Alt, BAU_points0, method="simple", df=T) %>% 
    cbind(BAU_points0$layer)
  BAU_alt0 = weighted.mean(x=BAU_alt0_df[,2], w=BAU_alt0_df[,3])
  
  # Mean soil moisture of all the points, weighted by the biomass
  BAU_sm0_df = raster::extract(SoilMoist, BAU_points0, method="simple", df=T) %>% 
    cbind(BAU_points0$layer)
  BAU_sm0 = weighted.mean(x=BAU_sm0_df[,2], w=BAU_sm0_df[,3])
  
  ## Centroid of the final distribution of biomass of the species i(t=100)
  BAU_year100NoDef = paste(BAU_input,BAU_ListData[id100],sep="") %>% raster()
  BAU_year100 = raster(vals=getValues(BAU_year100NoDef),
                      nrow=NrowRef,ncol=NcolRef,resolution=ResRef,
                      xmn=XminRef, xmx=XmaxRef,ymn =YminRef,ymx=YmaxRef,crs=CRSRef)
  BAU_points100 = rasterToPoints(BAU_year100, fun = function(x){x>=1}, spatial = T)
  BAU_Centroid100 = wt.centroid(BAU_points100,"layer", sp=T)
  
  # Mean altitude of all the points, weighted by the biomass
  BAU_alt100_df = raster::extract(Alt, BAU_points100, method="simple", df=T) %>%
    cbind(BAU_points100$layer)
  BAU_alt100 = weighted.mean(x=BAU_alt100_df[,2], w=BAU_alt100_df[,3])
  
   # Mean soil moisture of all the points, weighted by the biomass
  BAU_sm100_df = raster::extract(SoilMoist, BAU_points100, method="simple", df=T) %>%
    cbind(BAU_points100$layer)
  BAU_sm100 = weighted.mean(x=BAU_sm100_df[,2], w=BAU_sm100_df[,3])
  
  ## Shift in coordinates of the centroids
  BAU_Migration_x = BAU_Centroid0@coords[1]-BAU_Centroid100@coords[1]
  BAU_Migration_y = BAU_Centroid0@coords[2]-BAU_Centroid100@coords[2]
  
  # Shift in Altitude
  BAU_Migration_alt = BAU_alt100-BAU_alt0
  
   # Shift in soil moisture
  BAU_Migration_sm = BAU_sm100-BAU_sm0
  
  ### Scenario 2 (adaptability):
  
  Adapty_year0NoDef = paste(Adapty_input,Adapty_ListData[id0],sep="") %>% raster()
  Adapty_year0 = raster(vals=getValues(Adapty_year0NoDef),
                      nrow=NrowRef,ncol=NcolRef,resolution=ResRef,
                      xmn=XminRef, xmx=XmaxRef,ymn =YminRef,ymx=YmaxRef,crs=CRSRef)
  Adapty_points0 = rasterToPoints(Adapty_year0, fun = function(x){x>=1}, spatial = T)
  Adapty_Centroid0 = wt.centroid(Adapty_points0,"layer", sp=T)
  
  Adapty_alt0_df = raster::extract(Alt, Adapty_points0, method="simple", df=T) %>%
    cbind(Adapty_points0$layer)
  Adapty_alt0 = weighted.mean(x=Adapty_alt0_df[,2], w=Adapty_alt0_df[,3])
  
  Adapty_sm0_df = raster::extract(SoilMoist, Adapty_points0, method="simple", df=T) %>%
    cbind(Adapty_points0$layer)
  Adapty_sm0 = weighted.mean(x=Adapty_sm0_df[,2], w=Adapty_sm0_df[,3])
  
  Adapty_year100NoDef = paste(Adapty_input,Adapty_ListData[id100],sep="") %>% raster()
  Adapty_year100 = raster(vals=getValues(Adapty_year100NoDef),nrow=NrowRef,
                        ncol=NcolRef,resolution=ResRef,
                        xmn=XminRef, xmx=XmaxRef,ymn =YminRef,ymx=YmaxRef,crs=CRSRef)
  Adapty_points100 = rasterToPoints(Adapty_year100, fun = function(x){x>=1}, spatial = T)
  Adapty_Centroid100 = wt.centroid(Adapty_points100,"layer", sp=T)
  
  Adapty_alt100_df = raster::extract(Alt, Adapty_points100, method="simple", df=T) %>%
    cbind(Adapty_points100$layer)
  Adapty_alt100 = weighted.mean(x=Adapty_alt100_df[,2], w=Adapty_alt100_df[,3])
  
  Adapty_sm100_df = raster::extract(SoilMoist, Adapty_points100, method="simple", df=T) %>%
    cbind(Adapty_points100$layer)
  Adapty_sm100 = weighted.mean(x=Adapty_sm100_df[,2], w=Adapty_sm100_df[,3])
  
  Adapty_Migration_x = Adapty_Centroid0@coords[1]-Adapty_Centroid100@coords[1]
  Adapty_Migration_y = Adapty_Centroid0@coords[2]-Adapty_Centroid100@coords[2]
  
  Adapty_Migration_alt = Adapty_alt100-Adapty_alt0
  
  Adapty_Migration_sm = Adapty_sm100-Adapty_sm0
  
  ### Position of the distribution area and functional group
  ### of the species i
  
  if (name == "TotalBiomass"){ # The total biomass raster
    #does not correspond to a species, so this values are empty.
    Distrib = ""
    Group = ""
  }else {
    Distrib = SpeciesData$Situation.of.NE.CA.in.the.distribution.area[which(SpeciesData$Name == name)]
    Group = SpeciesData$Functional.type.name[which(SpeciesData$Name == name)]
  }
  
  ### Compiling the information in a data frame
  
  Results = rbind(Results, c(name, "BAU", BAU_Migration_x, BAU_Migration_y,
                             BAU_Migration_alt, BAU_Migration_sm, Distrib, Group))
  Results = rbind(Results, c(name, "Adapty", Adapty_Migration_x,Adapty_Migration_y,
                             Adapty_Migration_alt, Adapty_Migration_sm, Distrib, Group))
  
#  progress(i, progress.bar = T)

}

III.B. Statistical analyses

III.B.1. West_Est axes

shapiro.test(ResultSp$Migration_x[which(ResultSp$Scenario=="BAU")])
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  ResultSp$Migration_x[which(ResultSp$Scenario == "BAU")]
## W = 0.86919, p-value = 0.001336
shapiro.test(ResultSp$Migration_x[which(ResultSp$Scenario=="Adapty")])
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  ResultSp$Migration_x[which(ResultSp$Scenario == "Adapty")]
## W = 0.90837, p-value = 0.01174

The p-value is significant, so the normality is invalidated. As the initial conditions of the two scenarios are the same, the means we want to compare come from paired samples. The test of mean comparison to use is then the Wilcoxon Rank Sum and Signed Rank Test.

Xmean_BAU = mean(ResultSp$Migration_x[which(ResultSp$Scenario=="BAU")])
Xsd_BAU = sd(ResultSp$Migration_x[which(ResultSp$Scenario=="BAU")])

Xmean_Adapty = mean(ResultSp$Migration_x[which(ResultSp$Scenario=="Adapty")])
Xsd_Adapty = sd(ResultSp$Migration_x[which(ResultSp$Scenario=="Adapty")])

data.frame("X coordinate Mean" = c(Xmean_BAU,Xmean_Adapty), "Standard error" = c(Xsd_BAU, Xsd_Adapty),
           row.names = c("Business as usual","adaptability"))
##                   X.coordinate.Mean Standard.error
## Business as usual          6008.352       11904.06
## adaptability              10756.447       12937.95
wilcox.test(ResultSp$Migration_x~ResultSp$Scenario, paired = T)
## 
##  Wilcoxon signed rank exact test
## 
## data:  ResultSp$Migration_x by ResultSp$Scenario
## V = 468, p-value = 1.381e-06
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0

The hight variability is is due to the species effect. No Glm (because )

DifTot = c("Name", "X_Dif", "Y_Dif", "Alt_Dif", "SoilMoist_Dif")

for(sp in ListNamesTot) {

BAU_X = Results$Migration_x[which(Results$Scenario=="BAU" & Results$Name==sp)]
Adapty_X = Results$Migration_x[which(Results$Scenario=="Adapty" & Results$Name==sp)]
Xdif = (BAU_X-Adapty_X)/BAU_X
  
BAU_Y = Results$Migration_y[which(Results$Scenario=="BAU" & Results$Name==sp)]
Adapty_Y = Results$Migration_y[which(Results$Scenario=="Adapty" & Results$Name==sp)]
Ydif = (BAU_Y-Adapty_Y)/BAU_Y

BAU_Alt = Results$Migration_Altitude[which(Results$Scenario=="BAU" & Results$Name==sp)]
Adapty_Alt = Results$Migration_Altitude[which(Results$Scenario=="Adapty" & Results$Name==sp)]
Altdif = (BAU_Alt-Adapty_Alt)/BAU_Alt

BAU_sm = Results$Migration_SoilMoist[which(Results$Scenario=="BAU" & Results$Name==sp)]
Adapty_sm = Results$Migration_SoilMoist[which(Results$Scenario=="Adapty" & Results$Name==sp)]
smdif = (BAU_sm-Adapty_sm)/BAU_sm

DifTot = rbind(DifTot, c(sp, Xdif, Ydif, Altdif, smdif))

III.B.2. North-South direction

shapiro.test(Results$Migration_y[which(Results$Scenario=="BAU")])
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  Results$Migration_y[which(Results$Scenario == "BAU")]
## W = 0.92563, p-value = 0.02963
shapiro.test(Results$Migration_y[which(Results$Scenario=="Adapty")])
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  Results$Migration_y[which(Results$Scenario == "Adapty")]
## W = 0.92451, p-value = 0.02761

The p-value is significant, so the normality is invalidated. As the initial conditions of the two scenarios are the same, the means we want to compare come from paired samples. The test of mean comparison to use is then the Wilcoxon Rank Sum and Signed Rank Test.

Ymean_BAU = mean(ResultSp$Migration_y[which(ResultSp$Scenario=="BAU")])
Ysd_BAU = sd(Results$Migration_y[which(ResultSp$Scenario=="BAU")])

Ymean_Adapty = mean(ResultSp$Migration_y[which(ResultSp$Scenario=="Adapty")])
Ysd_Adapty = sd(ResultSp$Migration_y[which(ResultSp$Scenario=="Adapty")])

data.frame("Y coordinate Mean" = c(Ymean_BAU,Ymean_Adapty), "Standard error" = c(Ysd_BAU, Ysd_Adapty),
           row.names = c("Business as usual","adaptability"))
##                   Y.coordinate.Mean Standard.error
## Business as usual         -7035.744       14873.04
## adaptability              -2656.509       14618.67
wilcox.test(ResultSp$Migration_y~ResultSp$Scenario, paired = T)
## 
##  Wilcoxon signed rank exact test
## 
## data:  ResultSp$Migration_y by ResultSp$Scenario
## V = 423, p-value = 0.0003146
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0

The hight variability is is due to the species effect.
